{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:47:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:47:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17679"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17679"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.25,0.72,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10477"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24296"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPlasma osmolarity is a physiological parameter that must be tightly regulated to maintain cellular homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary determinant of plasma osmolarity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose concentration","Potassium concentration","Protein concentration","Sodium concentration","Urea concentration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E and its accompanying anions account for approximately 85-90% of plasma osmolarity. As the most abundant osmotically active solute in the extracellular fluid, sodium is the primary determinant of plasma osmolarity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E contributes minimally to plasma osmolarity due to its low extracellular concentration, despite its importance inside cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose concentration\u003C/strong\u003E typically contributes only about 5 mOsm/L to plasma osmolarity under normal physiological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea concentration\u003C/strong\u003E does not effectively influence osmolarity because it freely crosses cell membranes and therefore cannot create osmotic gradients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E has minimal effect on osmolarity because proteins have large molecular sizes and are present in relatively low concentrations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe calculated plasma osmolarity can be estimated using the formula: 2[Na+] + [glucose] + [urea], which highlights the dominant contribution of sodium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osmolarity is the concentration of osmotically active particles per litre of solution.","The major determinant of plasma osmolarity is sodium concentration.","Normal plasma osmolarity is maintained between 285-295 mOsm/L."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17679"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T08:08:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:49:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","